Building on my current work in analog frontend design and computational neuroscience, I am applying to the Research Associates Program to study how neural circuits are assembled and calibrated during development, under the mentorship of the Schoppik Lab.

My master's thesis with Dr. Jabeom Koo at Cooper Union designs a low-noise amplifier for brain--machine interfaces --- an application-specific integrated circuit for measuring local field and action potentials, shaped by the constraints of resolving microvolt-scale brain signals at ultra-low power consumption. My research with Dr. Stanislav Mintchev complements this from the theoretical side: I study how networks of neurons learn from delayed feedback. When a reward signal arrives seconds after the relevant neural activity and is broadcast to every connection in the network, how does the correct connection get selectively strengthened? I am mapping where this strengthening succeeds and how it breaks down across different conditions and feedback signals. At Mount Sinai, I trained a surgical instrument recognition model to improve operating room efficiency; being present during surgeries revealed aspects of the workflow I would never have known to ask about, and that understanding was critical to the model I built.

These experiences have reinforced my belief that the most effective tools come from understanding the system they are built for. In neuroscience, the brain remains incompletely characterized, which is why I pursue a theoretical grounding in how neural circuits behave, not as a separate interest from the engineering, but rather a prerequisite to doing it well.

At NYU Langone's Long Lab, I continued exploring engineering solutions built for biological systems. I built a computational pipeline for analyzing avian vocalizations and developed a robotic budgerigar as part of an automated system for minimally supervised vocal learning experiments. Designing that system required working directly with the birds, not just hypothesizing from a distance. I expected the robot would need to be hyper-realistic, but observed that the birds cuddled with even obviously-plastic, static models; this shifted my priorities toward the overall system rather than the physical robot. Through lab meetings, I encountered the idea of sleep replay: that the song motor circuit replays its learned patterns during sleep. I was surprised that a circuit would reproduce its waking activity without any external input; I now want to understand how this replay affects development and how such circuits are assembled.

The Schoppik Lab works on a related problem. Leary et al. (2025) showed that the vestibulo-ocular reflex circuit in zebrafish matures entirely without sensory experience, its development limited not by the brain but by the neuromuscular junction. This raised a further question: if this circuit calibrates itself from within, when does experience-dependent plasticity take over, and what is it for? I want to contribute to this work, from developing experimental apparatus like the lab's Tilt In Place Microscopy system to conducting the imaging and electrophysiology experiments.

My long-term goal is a PhD in which I design neural recording and experimental tools informed by firsthand experience in biological research. The Research Associates Program would provide the foundation for that trajectory. My time in the Long Lab has shown me how much I stand to learn from NYU Langone's neuroscience community. I had studied two-photon imaging in coursework, but when lab members walked me through the full optical setup, the gap between theory and practice became clear. I am eager to close that gap in the Schoppik Lab.
